<section id="glossary">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="kicker">Glossary</div>
      <h2>Key terms, plainly explained.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="glossary-grid stagger">
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Mesoscale scaffold</div>
        <p>The relatively stable community structure of the symptom network — the broad modular organization that persists even when influence shifts across phases.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Minimum dominating set <span class="term-abbr">MDS</span></div>
        <p>The smallest set of nodes that covers the whole graph directly or through neighbors. Defines which symptoms can serve as drivers.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Control frequency <span class="term-abbr">CF</span></div>
        <p>Proportion of exact minimum dominating sets in which a symptom appears. High CF = repeated participation in driver solutions.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Avg. control frequency <span class="term-abbr">ACF</span></div>
        <p>Mean normalized CF within a module. Informative descriptively, but less stable under case loss than AMCS.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="glossary-item">
        <div class="glossary-term">Avg. module control strength <span class="term-abbr">AMCS</span></div>
        <p>Directed summary of how strongly one module dominates another. The manuscript's key mesoscale metric.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

